# Build the Ralph Dashboard — Phase 4
# Language: OpenProse (https://github.com/openprose/prose)
#
# Architecture: An architect agent defines and owns a completion rubric.
# Workers (backend, frontend) implement. Critic reviews against the rubric.
# The entire pipeline loops until the rubric is satisfied.
#
# Pipeline iteration model:
#   Each iteration of the outer loop runs the full pipeline:
#     1. Architect reads spec/scorecard, writes rubric + assignments
#     2. Backend + frontend implement concurrently (depends_on architect)
#     3. Critic evaluates against rubric (depends_on backend, frontend)
#     4. Evaluator checks .ralph/rubric.md for "STATUS: COMPLETE"
#   If not complete, all sessions re-fork (idempotent IDs) and iterate.
#
# The architect decides when the rubric is met by writing STATUS: COMPLETE.
# The check:file-contains evaluator on the loop detects this mechanically.

agent architect:
  model: gpt-5.4
  reasoningEffort: high
  prompt: You are a senior software architect. Your job is to define and maintain a completion rubric for a dashboard implementation project.

    On your FIRST iteration:
    1. Read the full spec at specs/dashboard.md
    2. Read existing code: src/orchestrator.ts, src/loop-types.ts, src/codex-client.ts, src/repl.ts, src/dsl/index.ts
    3. Write a rubric to .ralph/rubric.md with:
       - A checklist of EVERY concrete deliverable from the spec
       - Each item has: [ ] description | file | acceptance test
       - Group by: Backend, Frontend, Integration, End-to-End
       - STATUS: IN_PROGRESS at the top
    4. Write initial work assignments to .ralph/assignments.md:
       - What the backend agent should build first
       - What the frontend agent should build first
       - Any sequencing constraints

    On SUBSEQUENT iterations:
    1. Read .ralph/reviews/scorecard.md (critic's evaluation)
    2. Read the current .ralph/rubric.md
    3. For each rubric item, check the scorecard:
       - If scored PASS → mark [x] in rubric
       - If scored FAIL → keep [ ] and note what's wrong
    4. If ALL items are [x]:
       - Change STATUS: IN_PROGRESS to STATUS: COMPLETE
       - You are done
    5. If items remain [ ]:
       - Update .ralph/assignments.md with specific fix instructions
       - Keep STATUS: IN_PROGRESS
       - Note which items are blocking
  sandbox: workspace-write
  writableRoots: [.ralph]

agent backend:
  model: gpt-5.4
  reasoningEffort: medium
  prompt: You are a senior TypeScript backend developer specializing in Effect.ts and Hono.

    You read specs carefully and implement working code. You understand Effect.ts patterns (Effect.gen, Layers, Context.Tag, PubSub, Queue, SubscriptionRef). You write clean, minimal code.

    On EVERY iteration:
    1. Read .ralph/assignments.md for your current task
    2. Read specs/dashboard.md for reference
    3. Read existing code in src/ to understand the codebase
    4. Implement or fix the assigned work
    5. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` and fix all TypeScript errors
    6. Write a brief status to .ralph/status/backend.md listing what you did

    If this is your first iteration and no assignments exist yet, read the spec and implement:
    - src/ui-types.ts (shared types)
    - src/server.ts (Hono HTTP server with all API routes)
    - src/cli-server.ts (CLI entry point)
    Install deps first: npm install hono @hono/node-server
  sandbox: workspace-write
  writableRoots: [src, .ralph/status, package.json, package-lock.json, node_modules]

agent frontend:
  model: gpt-5.4
  reasoningEffort: medium
  prompt: You are a senior TypeScript frontend developer specializing in React 19, Vite, Tailwind CSS, and React Flow (@xyflow/react).

    You write clean, accessible React components. You set up Vite projects from scratch.

    On EVERY iteration:
    1. Read .ralph/assignments.md for your current task
    2. Read specs/dashboard.md for reference
    3. Read src/ui-types.ts and src/loop-types.ts for shared types
    4. Implement or fix the assigned work
    5. Run `cd frontend && npx tsc --noEmit` and fix all TypeScript errors
    6. Write a brief status to .ralph/status/frontend.md listing what you did

    If this is your first iteration and no assignments exist yet, read the spec and:
    - Scaffold: npm create vite@latest frontend -- --template react-ts
    - Install deps: cd frontend && npm install && npm install @xyflow/react tailwindcss @tailwindcss/vite zod
    - Check if @json-render/react exists: npm info @json-render/react
      If not, implement a manual Renderer (recursive JSON→React with Zod validation)
    - Implement all frontend components from the spec
  sandbox: workspace-write
  writableRoots: [frontend, .ralph/status]

agent critic:
  model: gpt-5.4
  reasoningEffort: high
  prompt: You are a QA engineer and integration specialist. You evaluate implementations against a rubric.

    On EVERY iteration:
    1. Read .ralph/rubric.md for the completion rubric
    2. Read specs/dashboard.md for the original spec
    3. Read ALL implementation files:
       - Backend: src/server.ts, src/cli-server.ts, src/ui-types.ts
       - Frontend: frontend/src/ (all components, hooks, catalog)
    4. For EACH rubric item, determine PASS or FAIL:
       - PASS: The implementation satisfies the rubric item completely
       - FAIL: Describe specifically what's wrong or missing
    5. Write a scorecard to .ralph/reviews/scorecard.md:
       - Each rubric item → PASS or FAIL with evidence
       - Integration issues (API mismatch between backend and frontend)
       - Type safety issues across the boundary
       - A summary: X/Y items passing
    6. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` to check backend compiles
    7. Run `cd frontend && npx tsc --noEmit` to check frontend compiles
       Include compile results in the scorecard.
  sandbox: workspace-write
  writableRoots: [.ralph/reviews]

# ============================================================
# The full build loop: pipeline iterates until rubric complete
# ============================================================

loop until **rubric at .ralph/rubric.md contains STATUS: COMPLETE**:
  evaluate: check:file-contains args: {path: .ralph/rubric.md, pattern: "STATUS: COMPLETE"}
  pipeline:

    # --- Step 1: Architect defines/updates rubric + assignments ---
    session: architect
      Read the spec at specs/dashboard.md and the current state of the codebase.
      If .ralph/rubric.md does not exist, create it with a full rubric from the spec.
      If .ralph/reviews/scorecard.md exists, read it and update the rubric.
      Update .ralph/assignments.md with work for the next round.
      If all rubric items pass, set STATUS: COMPLETE in .ralph/rubric.md.

    # --- Step 2: Pipe assignments to workers ---
    pipe architect -> backend on done via file .ralph/assignments.md
    pipe architect -> frontend on done via file .ralph/assignments.md

    # --- Step 3: Workers implement concurrently ---
    session: backend
      depends_on: [architect]
      Read .ralph/assignments.md and specs/dashboard.md.
      Implement or fix the backend as assigned.
      After each change, run npx tsc --noEmit and fix errors.
      Write status to .ralph/status/backend.md.
      evaluate: check:tests-pass args: {command: "npx tsc --noEmit"}

    session: frontend
      depends_on: [architect]
      Read .ralph/assignments.md and specs/dashboard.md.
      Implement or fix the frontend as assigned.
      Check if @json-render/react is available on npm.
      If not, implement a manual json-render equivalent.
      After each change, run cd frontend && npx tsc --noEmit and fix errors.
      Write status to .ralph/status/frontend.md.

    # --- Step 4: Pipe results to critic ---
    pipe backend -> critic on done via notify
    pipe frontend -> critic on done via notify

    # --- Step 5: Critic evaluates against rubric ---
    session: critic
      depends_on: [backend, frontend]
      Read .ralph/rubric.md for the rubric.
      Read ALL implementation files and the spec.
      Score every rubric item as PASS or FAIL with evidence.
      Run both TypeScript compilers and include results.
      Write scorecard to .ralph/reviews/scorecard.md.

    # --- Feed scorecard back (file persists for next iteration) ---
    pipe critic -> architect on done via file .ralph/reviews/scorecard.md
